<br>
Most guild members fall in between, most leaning towards samaritans. Most are also followers, who feel a sense of loyalty to their guild. They will follow the example of whoever is leading their group/guild at the time. So when a PUNK is in charge, it rubs off on the members a bit as they try to stick together. That doesn't make them all PUNKS, but every guildmember needs to realize that their personal actions reflect on their guild, good and bad.<br>
<br>
A guild needs to identify these PUNKS and decide if they are worth the grief they will inflict on the guild. Its all relative to their sense of community among other guilds.<br>
<br>
It is also sad that many samaritans begin to change into PUNKS as they level higher. I had the educational experience to be forced to play a lower level character for a time. I found that players the same level as my main wouldnt even be bothered to speak to me when I asked them a question, as if I was a subspecies not worthy of notice. Not once did I ask for any free stuff from them. They only seemed to speak to me when they needed MY help to complete a quest that TLC prevents them from  completeing themselves. It made me sit back and wonder if I have ever treated anyone that harshly.<br>
<br>
So, there is and always will be arrogance in the game that will make it unpleasant for others. We can only stop to look at ourselves and try to treat others as we WANT to be treated, rather than how we HAVE been treated.<br>
<br>
Xianya Lilboomer<br>
